{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Review: Crop adaptation through historical introgression from wild relatives\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0  Authors: Garrett M. Janzen\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0  Li Wang\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0  Matthew B. Hufford\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The traditional paradigm in crop domestication has been origin from a wild relative within one or more defined geographic centers followed by expansion to the modern-day extent of cultivation. Absent from this paradigm are the effects of hybridization between diffusing domesticates and closely-related, locally-adapted wild relatives outside the center of origin. New methods have recently been employed to detect genome-wide patterns of introgression in a number of species. In this review, we will: 1) briefly describe these methods and provide a summary of their recent application for detection of crop-wild introgression, 2) review evidence supporting the hypothesis that wild-to-crop introgression has conferred local adaptation, 3) consider how the prevalence of this introgression alters traditional concepts of domestication, and 4) describe future advances in both basic and applied genetics that can be made through the study of introgression in agroecosystems.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Introgression methods and their recent applications\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The recent availability of genome-wide resequencing and reduced-representation genotyping ({\i e.g.}, GBS and RAD-Seq) data combined with new analytical methods have facilitated comprehensive study of introgression across a number of species ({\b Table 1}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab High-density marker data can be used with haplotype-based and other methods to assign specific genomic regions to a taxon of origin and to identify introgression across taxa .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab In several instances, introgression has been found to be conserved across individuals and populations suggesting an adaptive role:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 a.\tx360\tab Adaptive introgression has been discovered from Neanderthals and other archaic hominins into humans at loci controlling skin pigmentation, defense against pathogens, and tolerance of high altitude (reviewed in ).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 b.\tx360\tab Introgression across butterfly species at protective color-pattern loci has conferred M\u252?llerian mimicry (; {\b Figure 1}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 c.\tx360\tab Adaptive introgression across mosquito species has spread insecticide resistance .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 d.\tx360\tab Introgression across {\i Mimulus} ({\i i.e.}, monkeyflower) species has resulted in adaptation to pollinator preference and has contributed to speciation .\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Identification of introgression across a wide range of taxa at loci controlling a variety of adaptive traits suggests it has been an important evolutionary force.\sa180\par}
