{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Crop adaptation through introgression\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Over the last few years, several high-profile publications based on genome-wide data have documented introgression between crops and wild relatives outside putative domestication centers. A history of introgression during diffusion appears to be the rule for crops rather than the exception.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Crops, given their frequent history of diffusion from defined centers of origin, are ideal recipients of adaptive introgression. Theory suggests that such colonizing species will overwhelmingly be recipients rather than donors of introgression .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Empirical studies have revealed that introgression has occurred in many of the world\u8217's most important crops ({\b Table 2}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 a.\tx360\tab Maize: As maize spread from a lowland center of origin into the Mexican highlands it received introgression from a highland-adapted wild relative .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 b.\tx360\tab Sunflower: Domesticated sunflower has received substantial introgression from wild relatives post-domestication that has potentially reintroduced a branching morphology .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 c.\tx360\tab Rice: Introgression appears to have played an important role in the history of rice. Japonica rice cultivars were likely domesticated first from wild rice populations in southern China, and indica cultivars later developed through hybridization of ancient japonica with new wild rice populations in south and southeast Asia .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 d.\tx360\tab Barley: Landraces of barley show shared ancestry with geographically-proximate populations of wild relatives suggesting introgression .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 e.\tx360\tab Olive: Hybridization between wild and domesticated olive has been prevalent throughout the Mediterranean Basin .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 f.\tx360\tab Cassava: Substantial introgression from a closely-related wild species has been found in cassava, occurring both naturally and through a targeted breeding program for disease resistance .\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Predictions regarding the likelihood of adaptive introgression in additional crops can be made through comparison of their centers of origin to both their current extent of cultivation and the distribution of wild relatives across environmental gradients ({\b Figure 2}).\sa180\par}
